com.siperian.sif.message.hm

Class AddRelationshipRequest

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.siperian.sif.message.SiperianRequest
      • com.siperian.sif.message.hm.RelationshipRequestBase
        • com.siperian.sif.message.hm.AddRelationshipRequest
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    DataProvider, ModifyRelationshipRequest, Serializable

    public class AddRelationshipRequest
extends RelationshipRequestBase
implements DataProvider, ModifyRelationshipRequest
    Add a new Relationship/effective period for an existing relationship. between two Entities. The Entity Types of the Entities being related (and thus the Base Objects containing those Entities) are inferred from the Relationship Type. Each Relationship Type relates two Entity Types as defined in the Hierarchy Manager configuration.

    A new relationship is created if there is no other relationship of the same type between the specified entities. If the relationship is already present a new effective period is created.

    This request cannot be used to add a new Relationship with Foreign Key Relationship Type because adding a FK Relationship really involves updating an existing record in the FK Relationship Base Object. For more information, see UpdateRelationshipRequest.

    Required Parameters:

    • RelationshipRequestBase.setHmConfigurationUid(String) - UID of the HM Configuration. For more information, see RelationshipRequestBase.
    • RelationshipRequestBase.setRelTypeUid(String) - UID of the Relationship Type. The Relationship Type UID and the HM Configuration UID determine the Relationship Base Object. For more information, see RelationshipRequestBase.
    • RelationshipRequestBase.setRecordKey(RecordKey) - Key for the Relationship record being added. For more information, see RelationshipRequestBase.
    • setHierarchyUid(String) - Hierarchy UID for the Relationship record being added.
    • setBo1RecordKey(RecordKey) - First Entity in the Relationship.
    • setBo2RecordKey(RecordKey) - Second Entity in the Relationship.

    Usage Example:

    The following example adds a new Relationship record between two Entities. ROWID_OBJECT values for the two Entities are "123" and "789". The System for the new Relationship record is "Accounting" and the primary key for the Relationship record in the "Accounting" System is "ACCT-128".

    AddRelationshipRequest request = new AddRelationshipRequest();
    request.setHmConfigurationUid("HM_CONFIGURATION.Default|Master");
    request.setRelTypeUid("HM_RELATIONSHIP_TYPE.WorksFor");
    request.setHierarchyUid("HM_HIERARCHY.Customer");
    request.setRecordKey(RecordKey.sourceKey("ACCT-128", "Accounting"));
    request.setBo1RecordKey(RecordKey.rowid("123"));
    request.setBo2RecordKey(recordKey.rowid("789"));
    AddRelationshipResponse response = (AddRelationshipResponse) siperianClient.process(request);

    // Log the information in the response.
    RecordKey key = response.getRecordKey();
    log.info("Added Relationship record: " + key.getRowid());

    See Also:
    RecordKey, Record, RelationshipRequestBase, AddRelationshipResponse, UpdateRelationshipRequest, HubStateIndicator, SiperianRequest, Serialized Form

    API Pair: AddRelationshipResponse

    API Group: Data Update

        public void setPending(boolean setAsPending)
        If true, state of the new Relationship record is set to PENDING. The default value for a new Relationship record is ACTIVE.

        The state can only be set to PENDING if State Management is enabled for the Relationship Base Object to which the Relationship record is being added. For more information, see HubStateIndicator.
